{{Infobox video game | title = 140 | collapsible = | state = | image = 140 game cover.svg | caption = | developer = Jeppe Carlsen / Abstraction Games | publisher = [[Double Fine Productions]] (console versions) | series = | engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]] | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], [[Wii U]] | released = {{Unbulleted list|'''Windows''', '''OS X''', '''Linux'''|October 16, 2013|'''Xbox One'''|August 30, 2016|'''PlayStation 4''', '''Wii U'''|September 1, 2016}} | genre = [[Platform game|Platform]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] }}
'''''140''''' is a [[Platform game|platform]] game independently developed by Jeppe Carlsen, known for his gameplay direction for [[Playdead]]'s ''[[Limbo (video game)|Limbo]]''. The game is described as a "minimalistic platformer", using electronic music to create [[synesthesia]] as the player makes his way through 4 different levels, each with their own soundtrack.<ref name="gi"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.igf.com/php-bin/entry2013.php?id=666 | title = 140 - Entrant Page | publisher = [[Independent Games Festival]] | date = 2013 | accessdate = February 14, 2013 }}</ref> The gameplay has been compared to other similar games which involve music synchronization like ''[[Sound Shapes]]'' and the ''[[Bit.Trip]]'' series, though with difficult platforming elements comparable to games in the ''[[Mega Man]]'' series.<ref name="gi">{{Cite web | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/games/140/b/pc/archive/2013/02/14/limbo-designer-39-s-new-game-is-surreal.aspx | title = Limbo Designer's New Game Is Surreal | first = Adam | last = Biesenner | date = February 14, 2013 | accessdate = February 14, 2013 | work = [[Game Informer]] }}</ref><ref name="eurogamer"/> The game was released on [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], and [[Linux]] systems in October 2013, on [[Xbox One]] in August 2016, and on [[PlayStation 4]] as well as on [[Wii U]] in September 2016. A release on [[Playstation Vita]] and [[Nintendo 3DS]] was planned, but later cancelled<ref>{{cite web |last=Carlsen |first=Jeppe |url=https://twitter.com/CarlsenGames/status/830701321862934528 |title=it has unfortunately been cancelled, 3DS as well.|publisher=Twitter.com |date=2017-02-12 |accessdate=2018-07-22}}</ref>.
==Gameplay== As described by Carlsen, ''140'' is "an old school platformer", but where the challenge is "in syncing up your moves and jumps to the music-controlled elements"; as the player progresses through a level, the music will change reflecting the difficulty of the platforming elements.<ref name="eurogamer">{{Cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-02-14-limbo-dev-shows-off-pet-project-140 | title = Limbo dev shows off pet project 140 | first = Jeffrey | last = Matulef | date = February 14, 2013 | accessdate = February 14, 2013 | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> The player controls a geometric shape - a square when stationary, a circle when moving, and a triangle when jumping, across a two-dimensional environment made up of other simple geometric shapes, with the object to reach the end of the course. Various obstacles and enemies, also represented by geometric shapes, test the player's skills, and should the shape fall or be hit by one of these, they will need to restart at the last checkpoint they passed. Many of these obstacles and enemies have actions that are synchronized to the music, aiding the player in moving through the course; platforms that appear and disappear will do so on the beat, while enemies will fire in time to the music.<ref name="edge review">{{cite web | url = http://www.edge-online.com/review/140-review/ | title = 140 review | publisher = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] | date = 2013-10-16 | accessdate = 2013-10-16 }}</ref>
==Development== [[File:Jeppe Carlsen - Game Developers Conference 2011 - Day 3.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Jeppe Carlsen at the 2011 [[Game Developers Conference]]]] ''140'' was a project developed by Carlsen in his off-hours from Playdead. The idea originally grew out of Carlsen's attempt at an old school platformer, akin to ''[[Mega Man]]'', that involved throwing a ball that would travel in straight lines and bounce off walls to trigger effects. Carlsen also used the project to learn about the [[Unity (game engine)|Unity game engine]].<ref name="edge dev">{{Cite web | url = http://www.edge-online.com/news/140-a-synthesis-of-sound-and-play-from-playdeads-puzzle-mastermind-jeppe-carlsen/ | title = 140, a synthesis of sound and play from Playdead’s puzzle mastermind Jeppe Carlsen | first = Neil | last = Long | date = 2013-10-14 | accessdate = 2013-10-16 | work = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] }}</ref> As he started to add audio samples to the game, he found an interesting juxtaposition between the normal platform elements and the music, where the level would "dance to the music", and refocused the game towards its final form.<ref name="gamasutra road to idf"/> Carlsen had worked on the title for about two years, and enlisted the help of Jakob Schmid, a college friend and fellow employee at Playdead,<ref name="gamasutra road to idf">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/187261/Road_to_the_IGF_Jeppe_Carlsen_and_teams_140.php | title = Road to the IGF: Jeppe Carlsen and team's 140 | first = Christian | last = Nutt | date = 2013-02-25 | accessdate = 2013-03-13 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> who created all music and sound for the game, and Niels Fyrst and Andreas Peiterson for art.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2013/2/14/3987754/limbo-gameplay-designer-goes-deep-into-the-world-of-sounds-and-shapes | title = Limbo gameplay designer goes deep into the world of sounds and shapes with 140 | first = Emily | last = Gera | date = February 14, 2013 | accessdate = February 14, 2013 | publisher = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>
Carlsen announced in April 2016 that Abstraction Games and Double Fine Presents were helping to port the game to the [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[Xbox One]], [[Wii U]], and [[Nintendo 3DS]] with a release planned in Q4 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://blog.us.playstation.com/2016/04/20/introducing-colorful-platformer-140-on-ps4-ps-vita/ | title = Introducing Colorful Platformer 140 on PS4, PS Vita | first = Jeppe | last = Carlsen | date = April 20, 2016 | accessdate = April 20, 2016 | work = [[PlayStation Blog]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.usgamer.net/articles/double-fine-is-publishing-a-console-release-of-the-rhythm-game-140 | title = Double Fine is Publishing a Console Release of the Rhythm Game 140 | first = Nadia | last = Oxford |date = April 21, 2016 | accessdate = April 21, 2016 | work = [[US Gamer]] }}</ref> The Xbox One version was released on August 30, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://majornelson.com/2016/08/29/140-is-now-available-for-xbox-one/ | title = 140 Is Now Available For Xbox One | first = Larry | last= Hyrb | date = August 30, 2016 | accessdate = August 30, 2016 | work =Major Nelson's Xbox Blog }}</ref>
==Reception== The game won the "Excellence in Audio" category for the 2013 [[Independent Games Festival]] awards,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/189152/Cart_Life_FTL_Faster_Than_Light_Little_Inferno_take_home_IGF_awards.php | title = Cart Life, FTL: Faster Than Light, Little Inferno take home IGF awards | date = 2013-03-27 | accessdate = 2013-03-27 | publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> and was an honorary mention in the "Technical Excellence" category.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.igf.com/02finalists.html | title = 2013 Finalists | publisher = [[Independent Games Festival]] | date = 2013 | accessdate = February 14, 2013 }}</ref>
''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' considered the game to initially appear in stark contrast to Carlsen's earlier ''Limbo'', but as the player progresses in the game, the various mechanics of ''140'' show similar traits to many of the puzzles and situations that Carlsen had developed for ''Limbo''.<ref name="edge review"/> Ryan Cartmel of [[Hardcore Gamer]] gave the game a 4/5, calling it "gaming minimalism done right." <ref>{{cite web|last=Cartmel |first=Ryan |url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2013/10/17/review-140/58853/ |title=Review: 140 |publisher=Hardcore Gamer |date=2013-10-17 |accessdate=2013-10-18}}</ref> Derrick Sanskrit of [[The A.V. Club]]'s Gameological Society called ''140'' "a tightly paced and clever game of precise timing and jumping" and praised its minimalist structure that allows the player to focus on the rhythm and gameplay.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://gameological.com/2013/10/review-140/ | title = On the Beat | first = Derrick | last = Sanskrit | date = 2013-10-29 | accessdate = 2013-10-29 | publisher = [[The A.V. Club]] }}</ref>
